page.text: Rocky Mountain National Park (ROMO) is the most visited national park in Colorado with over 3
million visitors annually. The Town of Estes Park is the gateway community to ROMO, located
approximately three miles east of ROMO. Approximately 80% of ROMO visitors enter the park
through Estes Park, with the peak visitation occurring between June and September. Currently,
the Town of Estes Park and ROMO cooperatively operate a network of free transit services to
reduce parking demand and vehicular congestion in the Town and ROMO.
The Town of Estes Park is proposing the construction of a Transportation Hub (i.e., intercept
visitor parking lot) on the east side of the Town at the Visitor Center. U.S. Department of
Transportation Federal Transit Administration is funding the proposed Transportation Hub with
the grant from the Paul S. Sarbanes Transit in Parks Program (Transit in the Parks Program). It
will include a 217-space transit parking intercept garage, 29-space surface lot and six bus bays
to support transit services between Estes Park and ROMO. 100 parking spaces will continue to
be designated for short-term parking for the Visitor Center as stated in the Grant application.
The additional parking spaces constructed as part of this project would be designated for long-
term parking for visitors who wish to travel into ROMO and Estes Park via transit for an estimate
of 246 spaces (new garage and surface lot). Figure 1 shows the location of the Visitor Center
and proposed Transportation Hub relative to the major roadways in the area.
Due to the recent flooding in Estes Park and surrounding areas and the budgetary constraints
related to the flooding, the Transportation Hub is now planned to be constructed in two phases.
The Transportation Hub for Phase I, shown in Figure 2, will include:
 A 256-space lot – The lot is expected to be a three level parking structure (217 spaces)
located adjacent to the Estes Park Chamber of Commerce/Visitor Center with surface
parking (39 spaces) remaining on the western side of the Visitor Center.
 Six bus bays – The interment layout will include six bus bays to be constructed in the
vicinity of the Visitor Center, as shown in Figure 2, to accommodate the increased
frequency of bus service to the Transportation Hub. Two bus bays will be west of the
Visitor Center and four bus bays will be directly in front of the Visitor Center with a
turnaround loop to exit the site. Currently, bus service is provided every half hour from
the Estes Park Visitor’s Center to ROMO. This project would increase service frequency
to four times per hour (every 15 minutes).

Estes Park for traffic destined to ROMO along Fall River.
 Elkhorn Avenue (US 36) – This portion of US 36 (Elkhorn Avenue) is classified as a

The Visitor Center is on the eastern portion of the Town of Estes Park. East of the study area is
the Estes Park Golf Course, Sanitation Plant, Public Works and Parks and Recreation
maintenance facilities and main access to downtown Estes Park. The main part of downtown
Estes Park is located west of the intersection of US 34 / US 36.
Stanley Village Shopping Center is north of US 34, and its access is opposite the west access

i.b: Estes Park Chamber of Commerce/Visitor Center – Transporation Hub

page.text: Currently, the number of persons who use the alternative transportation system at peak
visitation are: approximately 26,000 passengers annually to the Town of Estes Park and
270,000 passengers annually to ROMO. By intercepting visitors east of the Estes Park, prior to
entering downtown Estes Park and ROMO, the planned Transportation Hub has the capacity to
eliminate more than 900 private auto trips daily from the busiest and most congested roads
accessing ROMO during the busy summer season.

i.b: Estes Park Transit Facility Parking Structure Traffic

page.text: The Transportation Hub will also reduce the demand for parking within ROMO by up to 300
spaces and reduce the number of visitors that park illegally in spaces designated for disabled
visitors and on road shoulders because of the lack of available legal spaces.
Annually, the Transportation Hub could reduce vehicular delay by 1,900 hours and eliminate
more than 900,000 vehicle miles of travel in ROMO and the Estes Park by reducing the number
of private auto trips made into ROMO and the overall length of vehicular trip made by visitors in
Parking demand in downtown Estes Park exceeds supply by more than 500 vehicles during
busy summer season. Visitors are forced to circulate through the congested downtown streets
Traffic volumes today on US 34/US 36 in downtown Estes Park exceed the roadway capacity
about 30 days during the summer visitor season. By 2020, volumes are expected to increase
from approximately 16,000 vehicles daily to 27,000 vehicles daily. Based on these projections, it
has been estimated that the local road network could be over capacity as many as 90 days
The over-capacity situation creates long delays and queues on Elkhorn Avenue in downtown
Estes Park for those traveling to ROMO. During today’s peak periods it takes approximately four
minutes to travel about one-sixth of a mile – an average of only 2.6 miles per hour.
The vast majority (80%) of vehicles accessing ROMO travel through the Estes Park. Two US
Highways (US 34 and US 36) and one State Highway (SH 7) are funneled through one major
intersection in downtown Estes Park on the way to ROMO, creating long delays and backups
through Estes Park. The congestion affects both residents and visitors travelling to downtown
Estes Park and through downtown to ROMO.
The Transportation Hub is anticipated to generate its highest traffic volumes on Saturdays;
therefore, existing Saturday summer peak hour volumes along vicinity roadways were used.
Traffic data was collected on two different Saturday during holiday weekends. The intersection
of US 34/ US 36 was collected 2011, the weekend before Fourth of July from 7 AM to 5 PM.
The Visitor Center access driveways were collected in 2011 the weekend of Labor Day from 10
AM to 3 PM. These volumes were blended to provide peak visitation Saturday conditions for the
three intersections and are shown on Figure 4.
As Figure 4 indicates, the existing conditions of the Visitor Center show higher outbound
utilization of the east access driveway. This is a result of the current internal circulation pattern.
When entering the west access driveway, the circulation is one-way heading to the eastern
(larger) portion of the parking lot. The east side of the parking lot also provides circulation that
directs existing vehicles to the east access driveway. Currently, only 23 spaces on the west side
of the Visitor Center has the option to exit using the west access driveway. Another notable

weighted average vehicle delay for all movements. For unsignalized intersections, levels of
service are calculated for each movement that must yield the right-of-way to other traffic
movements; levels of service are not calculated for free-flow movements, as they are not

parking for the existing Visitor Center as it is today and the second being the long-term parking
for the visitors parking who wish to travel into ROMO and Estes Park via transit.

vehicles per hour per space. Additionally, the distribution is 48% IN and 52% OUT of the Visitor
Center during the Saturday peak hour. The peak occupancy of the existing lots was 85% (130
The trip generation for the long-term parking is based on the ITE Land Use 090: Park-and-Ride

destinations. The peak hour rate from the ITE Trip Generation used is 0.71 and the daily traffic
The Visitor Center (short-term) parking is planned to be 100 parking spaces and the
Transportation Hub (long-term) parking is planned to be 156 spaces for Phase I. For Phase II,
the Visitor Center (short-term) parking will remain at 100 parking spaces and the Transportation
Hub (long-term) parking is planned to be 146 parking spaces.
The above information was used to generate the projected daily and peak hour trip forecasts for
Phase I and Phase II which are shown in Table 2. As Table 2 indicates, the Transportation Hub
will result in approximately 3,500 daily trips, with 375 occurring in the noon peak hour on a
Saturday for Phase I. As can be seen in Table 2, Phase II reduction in 10 parking spaces will
only decrease trip generation by 5 exiting vehicles during the peak hour. To be conservative
Phase I trip generation was used to evaluate for 2035 traffic conditions.

volumes take into account for 24 years of growth.

page.text: Access to the proposed Transportation Hub / Visitor Center was reviewed based on CDOT
State Highway Access Code related to auxiliary lane criteria.
The east access drive laneage configuration is planned to remain the same. Currently at the
east access driveway, the Visitor Center has an eastbound dedicated ingress right-turn lane and
westbound ingress left-turn lane. The right-turn lane represents a lane drop for eastbound traffic
along US 34 to go from two lanes to one lane farther to the east.
The egress laneage at the eastbound access will remain a dedicated left-turn lane and a
through/right-turn lane. The east access driveway will continue to provide access to Estes Park
Sanitation Plant, Public Works and Parks and Recreation Maintenance.
US 34 is classified as a NR-A which requires a right-turn deceleration lane for volumes more
than 25 vph as stated in CDOT’s State Highway Access Code (SHAC) criteria for auxiliary
lanes. The east access drive is right at this SHAC standard.
The west access drive ingress laneage configuration is planned to remain the same. A
westbound left-turn lane on US 34 is provided. There are two lanes eastbound on US 34: a
through lane and a through/right-turn lane. The existing 36 feet driveway will be modified from
two lanes (one inbound lane/one outbound lane) to three lanes (one inbound lane/ two
outbound lanes). The outbound lanes will be configured to provide a dedicated left-turn lane and
According to SHAC criteria for auxiliary lanes, the proposed Transportation Hub would be
required to install an eastbound right-turn lane as the eastbound right-turning movement is 84
vph and the projected volume will be 85 vph, both of which are higher than more than 25 vph or
Currently, the through/right-turn lane primarily operates as a right-turn lane due to the
termination of the through lane at the east access drive. It is recommended that the existing
configuration not be changed as it is currently working well. If an eastbound dedicated right-turn
lane were to be installed, it would need to be removed for Phase II as this auxiliary lane would
create conflicts and confusion with the future right-in bus only access driveway. There is
insufficient distance from the intersection at US 34 / US 36 for both improvements to operate

page.text: The Town of Estes Park is proposing the construction of a Transportation Hub (i.e., intercept
visitor parking lot) on the east side of the Town at the Visitor Center. U.S. Department of
Transportation Federal Transit Administration is funding the proposed Transportation Hub with
the grant from the Paul S. Sarbanes Transit in Parks Program (Transit in the Parks Program). It
would include a 217-space transit parking intercept garage, 29-space surface lot and six bus
bays to support transit services between the Town of Estes Park and ROMO. 100 parking
spaces will continue to be designated for short-term parking for the Visitor Center as stated in
the Grant application. The additional parking spaces constructed as part of this project would be
designated for long-term parking for visitors who wish to travel into ROMO and Estes Park via
transit for a total build out of 246 spaces.
The Transportation Hub is located east of the intersection of US 34 / US 36. Access for Phase I
is proposed via the two existing Visitor Center driveways. In the future, as part of the complete
build out (Phase II) an additional driveway will be constructed west of the Visitor Center to
provide right-in access for buses only.
The Transportation Hub is anticipated to generate its highest traffic volumes on Saturdays;
therefore, existing Saturday summer peak hour volumes along vicinity roadways were used.
The Visitor Center (short-term) parking is planned to be 100 parking spaces and the
Transportation Hub (long-term) parking is planned to be 246 spaces. Overall, the site will result
in approximately 3,500 daily trips, with 375 occurring in the noon peak hour on a Saturday.
Existing traffic conditions in the vicinity of the Visitor Center provide LOS D or better for the
signalized intersection of US 34 / US 36 and the majority of turning movements at the
unsignalized intersections. The southbound left-turn at the west access drive and the
northbound left-turn at the east access drive is LOS F.
2015 background traffic conditions remain the same as existing traffic conditions. The 2015
traffic conditions with the proposed Transportation Hub at the signalized intersection of US 34 /
US 36 will continue to operate at LOS D. The unsignalized intersection of US 34 / west access
drive will have a LOS F for the northbound movements out of the site. The intersection of US 34
/ east access drive will operate at LOS F for the northbound left-turn as well.
